[start section id="20112"]

#1 Cecal adenocarcinoma, stage IIIC (pT4b, N1b, M0) status-post surgical resection
#2 Elevated liver enzymes
#3 Acute renal failure, improving
I discussed with Mr. Vanguilder and his family his colon cancer diagnosis and prognosis.  Also discussed indications, alternatives, general logistics, and potential toxicities of adjuvant systemic chemotherapy treatment.  At this time, given his current situation of rising liver enzyme abnormalities and renal function that has not returned to baseline, he would not be able to safely start adjuvant chemotherapy.  However, he is only one-month out from surgery, and he could certainly be monitored in the next one-to-two months' time, that if he makes adequate recovery adjuvant systemic chemotherapy would certainly be considered for his stage of colon cancer, despite his senior age of 79.  In this setting we know that  in other patients without significant comorbidity that can tolerate adjuvant chemotherapy, there is a benefit to systemic adjuvant chemotherapy despite advanced age.  This may be in the form of 5-FU or capecitabine without the oxaliplatin.  However, this will need to be assessed as he makes his recovery.  This was discussed in extensive detail with the patient and family.  They do live closer to the WIC Hospital and prefer to establish care there.  I suggested that they make an appointment in approximately two-weeks' time to establish care there.
With regard to the elevated liver enzymes, this appeared to be slightly abnormal at the time of hospital admission on October 3.  Then, on yesterday's laboratory check, the enzymes were elevated.  At this time, since the CT-scan does not show any major abnormalities in the liver, we would recommend holding the Zocor until the liver enzymes improve.  Would recommend rechecking liver enzyme tests in about two-weeks' time.  If they are improving, then no further action needs to be done other than monitoring.  Zocor can certainly be restarted when liver enzymes return to normal.  If the liver enzymes continue to rise, we would consider ultrasound of the liver and fractionating the alkaline phosphatase for further evaluations.  This can be done at the WIC Hospital.
Regarding the incidental finding of the left renal mass that was only seen on ultrasound on October 4, 2010, at this time we would recommend followup imaging in the future.  This was not seen on CT-scan today.  No further testing is necessary at this time.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at CFCMCIC.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

